  "prompt": "Are barron\u2019s 333 high frequency words enough to get a 155+ score in verbal?",
  "response": "Barron's 333 High-Frequency Words is a helpful resource for improving vocabulary, especially for tests like the GRE or SAT. However, achieving a score of 155 or higher in the verbal section will typically require a more comprehensive vocabulary and understanding of various contextually used words.\n\nWhile the 333 words cover many commonly used, high-frequency terms, a strong verbal score also depends on your understanding of reading comprehension, critical reasoning, synonyms, antonyms, and the ability to analyze and interpret complex texts. It\u2019s beneficial to supplement your study of these high-frequency words with additional vocabulary resources, practice reading academic articles, and familiarize yourself with the types of questions you will encounter on the verbal section of the exam.\n\nIn summary, while the 333 words can provide a good foundational vocabulary, broadening your studies and practicing with a variety of materials will increase your chances of achieving a score of 155 or higher.",
